<paragraph blockId="16.[264,1324,284,950]" box="[264,402,284,309]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis box="[264,402,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[264,1324,284,950]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<typeStatus box="[312,421,324,350]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Holotype</typeStatus>
male. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[518,614,324,350]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Length:</emphasis>
8.0 mm. 
<emphasis box="[749,831,324,350]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[749,821,324,350]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Width</emphasis>
:
</emphasis>
<quantity box="[842,939,324,350]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="2.9">2.9 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[965,1145,324,350]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Color/Surface:</emphasis>
Dark reddishbrown, weakly shining. Dorsum (
<figureCitation box="[671,742,364,390]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="8.[264,382,1611,1635]" captionTargetBox="[272,1285,617,1590]" captionTargetId="figure-176@8.[264,1323,609,1604]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. 1, dorsal habitus of male Hilophyllus penai. 2, dorsal habitus of male H. argentinensis. 3, dorsal habitus of male holotype H. martinezi, n.sp. 4, dorsal view of head of female H. penai showing smaller antennal club, eyes, and mandibles. 5, dorsal view of head of male H. penai showing eyes and mandibles. 6, dorsal view of head of male H. argentinensis showing large eyes and bent, interlocking mandibles. Scale bar = 2 mm (Figs. 1–3) or 1 mm (Figs. 4–6)." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) almost uniformly covered with large punctures, most with a single elongate, apically acute scale (
<figureCitation box="[867,958,404,430]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–18" captionStartId="13.[264,383,1475,1499]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,567,1451]" captionTargetId="figure-216@13.[264,1323,555,1451]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 13–18. 13, detail of elytral surface of H. argentinensis showing scale, puncture, and smooth surface structure. Scale bar = 100 m. 14, detail of elytral surface of H. martinezi showing scale, puncture, and minutely­wrinkled surface structure. Scale bar = 100 m. 15, right antenna of male H. argentinensis. Scale bar = 200 m. 16, right antenna of male H. martinezi. Scale bar = 200 m. 17, scape of right antenna of male H. martinezi. Scale bar = 50 m. 18, external surface of apex of right paramere of male H. martinezi showing two minute teeth. Scale bar = 50 m." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[993,1067,404,430]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Head:</emphasis>
Eyes large, width of eyes together in dorsal view greater than narrowest interocular width. Mandibles small, externally rounded, not abruptly curved inward at middle; dorsal tooth acute; ventral tooth of right mandible minute (apex of right mandible broken). Antennal club segments elongate, longer than 1.5 times length of head (
<figureCitation box="[868,962,564,590]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–18" captionStartId="13.[264,383,1475,1499]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,567,1451]" captionTargetId="figure-216@13.[264,1323,555,1451]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 13–18. 13, detail of elytral surface of H. argentinensis showing scale, puncture, and smooth surface structure. Scale bar = 100 m. 14, detail of elytral surface of H. martinezi showing scale, puncture, and minutely­wrinkled surface structure. Scale bar = 100 m. 15, right antenna of male H. argentinensis. Scale bar = 200 m. 16, right antenna of male H. martinezi. Scale bar = 200 m. 17, scape of right antenna of male H. martinezi. Scale bar = 50 m. 18, external surface of apex of right paramere of male H. martinezi showing two minute teeth. Scale bar = 50 m." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1004,1135,564,590]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Pronotum:</emphasis>
Sides strongly explanate, explanate margin subequal to eye in width. Anterior angle produced beyond anterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[461,549,644,670]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–24" captionStartId="14.[264,383,1638,1662]" captionTargetBox="[300,1293,973,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-317@14.[300,1293,967,1617]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 19–24. 19, ventral view of male genitalia, H. penai. 20, ventral view of male genitalia, H. argentinensis. 21, ventral view of male genitalia, H. martinezi. 22, female genitalia of H. penai. Terminology as in Holloway (1998): BC = bursa copulatrix, H = hemisternite, H9 = ninth hemisternite, SD = spermathecal duct, SG? = spermathecal gland (not seen), SP = spermatheca, ST = stylus. 23, outline of anterior portion of pronotum of H. argentinensis, showing lack of produced anterior angles. 24, outline of anterior portion of pronotum of H. martinezi, showing produced anterior angles." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
). Lateral margin broadly rounded, widest before middle. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1238,1322,644,670]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Elytra:</emphasis>
Shape elongate. Almost uniformly punctate, most punctures with scales, punctures without scales forming longitudinal rows (not patches), scales brown and testaceous. Sutural interval and lateral margin elevated apically. Surface between punctures roughened (
<figureCitation box="[404,491,804,830]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–18" captionStartId="13.[264,383,1475,1499]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,567,1451]" captionTargetId="figure-216@13.[264,1323,555,1451]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 13–18. 13, detail of elytral surface of H. argentinensis showing scale, puncture, and smooth surface structure. Scale bar = 100 m. 14, detail of elytral surface of H. martinezi showing scale, puncture, and minutely­wrinkled surface structure. Scale bar = 100 m. 15, right antenna of male H. argentinensis. Scale bar = 200 m. 16, right antenna of male H. martinezi. Scale bar = 200 m. 17, scape of right antenna of male H. martinezi. Scale bar = 50 m. 18, external surface of apex of right paramere of male H. martinezi showing two minute teeth. Scale bar = 50 m." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
), appearing wrinkled at 40x. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[846,913,804,830]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Legs:</emphasis>
Mesotibiae lacking external tooth. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,452,844,870]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Male genitalia:</emphasis>
See 
<figureCitation box="[517,607,844,870]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–24" captionStartId="14.[264,383,1638,1662]" captionTargetBox="[300,1293,973,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-317@14.[300,1293,967,1617]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 19–24. 19, ventral view of male genitalia, H. penai. 20, ventral view of male genitalia, H. argentinensis. 21, ventral view of male genitalia, H. martinezi. 22, female genitalia of H. penai. Terminology as in Holloway (1998): BC = bursa copulatrix, H = hemisternite, H9 = ninth hemisternite, SD = spermathecal duct, SG? = spermathecal gland (not seen), SP = spermatheca, ST = stylus. 23, outline of anterior portion of pronotum of H. argentinensis, showing lack of produced anterior angles. 24, outline of anterior portion of pronotum of H. martinezi, showing produced anterior angles." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
. Parameres with 2 small, external teeth at apex (
<figureCitation box="[1218,1308,844,870]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–18" captionStartId="13.[264,383,1475,1499]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,567,1451]" captionTargetId="figure-216@13.[264,1323,555,1451]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 13–18. 13, detail of elytral surface of H. argentinensis showing scale, puncture, and smooth surface structure. Scale bar = 100 m. 14, detail of elytral surface of H. martinezi showing scale, puncture, and minutely­wrinkled surface structure. Scale bar = 100 m. 15, right antenna of male H. argentinensis. Scale bar = 200 m. 16, right antenna of male H. martinezi. Scale bar = 200 m. 17, scape of right antenna of male H. martinezi. Scale bar = 50 m. 18, external surface of apex of right paramere of male H. martinezi showing two minute teeth. Scale bar = 50 m." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
), median lobe cylindrical toward apex, not laterally compressed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[264,1324,284,950]" box="[312,522,924,950]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Female unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[264,1323,1004,1470]" box="[264,383,1004,1029]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis box="[264,383,1004,1029]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[264,1323,1004,1470]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
This species is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Paulsen &amp; Mondaca" authorityYear="2006" baseAuthorityName="Paulsen &amp; Mondaca" baseAuthorityYear="2006" box="[717,818,1044,1069]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Hilophyllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="penai">
<emphasis box="[717,818,1044,1069]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">H. penai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its unarmed mesotibiae. It is, however, externally quite similar to 
<emphasis box="[573,773,1084,1109]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName box="[573,769,1084,1109]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Ceratognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argentinensis">H. argentinensis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The most notable external difference between these two species is in the anterior angles of the pronotum, which are produced beyond the anterior pronotal margin in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Paulsen &amp; Mondaca" authorityYear="2006" box="[605,755,1164,1189]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Hilophyllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="martinezi">
<emphasis box="[605,755,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">H. martinezi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but more or less contiguous with the anterior margin of the pronotum in 
<taxonomicName box="[579,771,1204,1229]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Ceratognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argentinensis">
<emphasis box="[579,771,1204,1229]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">H. argentinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[788,872,1204,1230]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–24" captionStartId="14.[264,383,1638,1662]" captionTargetBox="[300,1293,973,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-317@14.[300,1293,967,1617]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 19–24. 19, ventral view of male genitalia, H. penai. 20, ventral view of male genitalia, H. argentinensis. 21, ventral view of male genitalia, H. martinezi. 22, female genitalia of H. penai. Terminology as in Holloway (1998): BC = bursa copulatrix, H = hemisternite, H9 = ninth hemisternite, SD = spermathecal duct, SG? = spermathecal gland (not seen), SP = spermatheca, ST = stylus. 23, outline of anterior portion of pronotum of H. argentinensis, showing lack of produced anterior angles. 24, outline of anterior portion of pronotum of H. martinezi, showing produced anterior angles." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
). This gives the overall impression of a smaller pronotum in 
<emphasis box="[529,683,1244,1269]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Paulsen &amp; Mondaca" authorityYear="2006" box="[529,679,1244,1269]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Hilophyllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="martinezi">H. martinezi</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Ideally we would prefer more material upon which to base a new species. However, the form of the male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[1082,1231,1284,1310]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–24" captionStartId="14.[264,383,1638,1662]" captionTargetBox="[300,1293,973,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-317@14.[300,1293,967,1617]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 19–24. 19, ventral view of male genitalia, H. penai. 20, ventral view of male genitalia, H. argentinensis. 21, ventral view of male genitalia, H. martinezi. 22, female genitalia of H. penai. Terminology as in Holloway (1998): BC = bursa copulatrix, H = hemisternite, H9 = ninth hemisternite, SD = spermathecal duct, SG? = spermathecal gland (not seen), SP = spermatheca, ST = stylus. 23, outline of anterior portion of pronotum of H. argentinensis, showing lack of produced anterior angles. 24, outline of anterior portion of pronotum of H. martinezi, showing produced anterior angles." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Figs. 20–21</figureCitation>
) in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Ceratognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argentinensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">H. argentinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Paulsen &amp; Mondaca" authorityYear="2006" box="[490,642,1324,1349]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Hilophyllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="martinezi">
<emphasis box="[490,642,1324,1349]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">H. martinezi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are vastly different. Based on the constancy of male genitalic form (
<emphasis box="[457,500,1364,1389]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">i.e.,</emphasis>
lack of variation) observed in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Paulsen &amp; Mondaca" authorityYear="2006" baseAuthorityName="Paulsen &amp; Mondaca" baseAuthorityYear="2006" box="[892,998,1364,1389]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Hilophyllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="penai">
<emphasis box="[892,998,1364,1389]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">H. penai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(n = 4), as well as in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Ceratognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argentinensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">H. argentinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(n = 9) across its range, we believe that the unique male genitalic form of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Paulsen &amp; Mondaca" authorityYear="2006" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Hilophyllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="martinezi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">H. martinezi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is compelling evidence that this is a distinct species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[264,901,1524,1710]" box="[264,518,1524,1550]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis box="[264,407,1524,1549]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Distribution</emphasis>
(
